{"title_page": "Lambton College", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2014}}\n{{Advert|date=January 2014}}\n}}\n{{Coord|42|58|49.89|N|82|20|54.91|W|display=title|type:edu}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = '''Lambton College of Applied Arts and Technology'''\n|image = Lambton College.png\n|image_size = 300px\n|motto = Connect\n|president = Judith Morris, President & CEO<ref name= \"Booth20111214\">{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 14 December 2011 |title= Judith Morris gets Lambton College top job, replacing retiring Tony Hanlon |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/judith-morris-gets-lambton-college-top-job-replacing-retiring-tony-hanlon/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\n|type = Public \n|undergrad    = \n|postgrad     = \n|established = 1969\n|city = [[Sarnia]],<br/>[[Mississauga]] and <br/>[[Toronto]]\n|state = [[Ontario]]\n|country = [[Canada]]\n|colours = [[White (color)|White]] and [[Blue (Colour)|Blue]]  {{color box|#00502F}} {{color box|#072B61}} |\n|students =  over 3,500 full-time, over 6,500 part-time, 500 international (on campus), over 3,500 international (off shore), 600 apprenticeship<ref name= \"Booth20111214\"/><ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.studycanada.ca/english/school_profile.php?SchoolID=127 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015091135/http://www.studycanada.ca/english/school_profile.php?SchoolID=127 |archivedate=October 15, 2008 }}{{Failed verification|date=January 2014}}<!-- information not on archived version of webpage --></ref>\n|publictransit   = \n|campus = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|free_label   = Sports teams\n|free         = Lambton Lions\n|mascot = Pounce\n|affiliations   =  [[Canadian Colleges Athletic Association|CCAA]], [[Association of Canadian Community Colleges|ACCC]], [[Association of Universities and Colleges of Canada|AUCC]], [[Canadian Bureau for International Education|CBIE]]\n|website = http://www.lambtoncollege.ca\n}}\n'''Lambton College''' is a publicly funded college in [[Sarnia]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It has approximately 3,500 full-time students, 6,500 part-time students and 3,500 international students worldwide. Lambton College also has campuses in [[Mississauga]] and [[Toronto]].<ref name= \"Booth20111214\"/>\n\n==Programs==\nLambton College has more than 90{{quantify|date=January 2014}} post-secondary programs and apprenticeships, academic upgrading, post-graduate, part-time and training programs. The college also has pathways that lead to credentialing.{{clarify|date=January 2014}}\n\nAcademic Schools:\n* School of Technology & Trades\n* School of Business & International Education\n* School of Health, Community Services & Creative Design\n* School of Fire Sciences\n* School of Information Technology\n* Online Education\n\n==Buildings and features==\nThe NOVA Chemicals Health & Research Centre was officially opened in May 2019. The facility is home to all Health Sciences programming labs and advanced technology simulation facilities. The Athletics & Fitness Complex opened in October 2018, and has a 15,000 sq. ft. double gymnasium with seating for 1,241 fans.\n\nCentre of Excellence in Energy & Bio-Industrial Technologies was designed to bring together academic programming, industry-standard training, and research labs. The official opening took place in September 2018 after a two-year, $14.2 million upgrade of the 34,000 sq. ft. facility, which also included the addition of 7,000 sq. ft. of training space.\n\nCreations Fine Dining is an on-campus restaurant and is an applied learning environment for the Hospitality & Tourism Management and Culinary Management programs.<ref name= \"Booth20110224\">{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 24 February 2011 |title= It's no accident: Lambton College works hard to attract new students |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/its-no-accident-lambton-college-works-hard-to-attract-new-students/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe Early Childhood Education Centre is a college training facility used by the Early Childhood Education program. It hosts Ontario Early Years Centre, now known as EarlyON. It is scheduled to close in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tyler |last= Kula |date= 13 November 2013 |title= Lambton College's Early Childhood Education Centre set to close by July, 2014 |newspaper= [[Sarnia Observer]] |url= http://www.theobserver.ca/2013/11/13/lambton-colleges-early-childhood-education-centre-set-to-close-by-july-2014 |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nFormerly known as the Fire & Public Safety Centre of Excellence, the campus was rebranded as The Fire School in spring 2019. It is an $11-million facility featuring a two-story structure with classrooms, a triple-truck bay, a fire tower and training props.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 3 December 2011 |title= Lambton College celebrates grand opening of new Fire and Public Safety Centre of Excellence |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-celebrates-grand-opening-of-new-fire-and-public-safety-centre-of-excellence/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe Skilled Trades Training Centre provides skilled trades and apprenticeship training with classrooms, and labs and facilities.<ref>{{cite web |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 9 December 2011 |title= Lambton College state of the art labs gives grad leg-up on career in trades |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-state-of-the-art-labs-gives-grad-leg-up-on-career-in-trades/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe Sustainable Smart Home is a $1.2 million building, featuring a cutting-edge energy management system, used for applied research and learning.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 24 June 2011 |title= Sustainable Smart Home opens at Lambton College |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/sustainable-smart-home-opens-at-lambton-college/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe SPA at Lambton is a teaching facility and a full-service spa, the spa is run and managed by students in Lambton's Esthetician and Hairstylist programs.<ref name= \"Booth20110224\"/>\n\n==Student life==\nLambton's Residence houses over 280 students and is located on campus. It includes a courtyard and a student lounge.\nEsports Arena on campus was the first of its kind at a Canadian college.\nThe new Athletics & Fitness Complex features a brand new Fitness Room that is free for students.\nEnactus Lambton is a student group, formed in early 2012, and were crowned World Champions at the 2018 Enactus World Cup, which took place in San Jose, California.\nThe Lambton College team competed with 30 other international college and university teams before the finals where they faced Egypt, India, and Morocco. They're the first Canadian College to ever take home the top prize.\n\n==History==\nIn 1966, Lambton College was the second college in the Ontario college system to officially open. At this time 45 students were enrolled in five programs at the college. The main campus' cornerstone was dedicated on June 4, 1970. The cornerstone is a [[time capsule]] containing coins, bills, stamps, the college calendar for 1970\u201371, a copy of the school's charter, the school seal, a copy of the land deed for the college among other items.\nThe first president of Lambton College was Wolfgang Franke. He started full-time duties in January 1967 and his starting salary was $18,000. The first faculty tour of the original site was delayed because the building housing the classrooms was locked and no one had the key. Faculty member Ron Lawrence discovered (much to his dismay) that his house key fit the lock.\nIn 1975 a sculpture commissioned by the school, ''[[Homage (sculpture)|Homage]]'', was constructed by artist [[Haydn Llewellyn Davies|Haydn Davies]]. The college destroyed the sculpture in 2005. The destruction of the sculpture has been controversial and was the subject of a lawsuit settled in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |first= James |last= Adams |title= College and sculptor resolve dispute over destroyed art |date= 23 August 2012 |origyear= 22 May 2010 |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/college-and-sculptor-resolve-dispute-over-destroyed-art/article4319964/ |newspaper= [[The Globe and Mail]] |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Alfoldy2012\">{{cite book |last= Alfoldy |first= Sandra |title= Allied Arts: Architecture and Craft in Postwar Canada |year= 2012 |publisher= McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP |isbn= 9780773539600 |pages= [https://books.google.com/books?id=4dUBJv6Rn_AC&pg=PA83 82\u20134] |chapter= Chapter 3: Scale and Form}}</ref>\n\n==International==\nLambton's international programming began in 1996 with an initiative in China.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |title= Lambton's international flavour no accident for academic strategists looking to the future |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambtons-international-flavour-no-accident-for-academic-strategists-looking-to-the-future/ |date= 13 May 2011 |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref> The international department at Lambton now includes campuses in China, Nigeria and Saudi Arabia and there are between 380 and 500 international students on-campus and 3,500 at international campuses.<ref name= \"Booth20111214\"/><ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 17 July 2011 |title= Lambton College making its global mark |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-making-its-global-mark/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==Scholarships and bursaries==\nLambton College offers a variety of scholarships and bursaries.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 21 November 2011 |title= Lambton College scholarships total nearly $85k this year |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-scholarships-total-nearly-85k-this-year/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mylambton.ca/financial_aid/home |title= Financial Aid Home |work= mylambton.ca}}</ref> Lambton College scholarships for [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]], [[First Nations]] and [[M\u00e9tis]] students include: Aboriginal Post Secondary Education & Training Bursary.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/eng/4078514441563/4078514441563?sb=bn&q=Lambton+College&bp=&fs=000&ag=000&srcDC=10 |title= Aboriginal Post Secondary Education & Training Bursary: Lambton College |publisher= [[Aboriginal Affairs and Northern Development Canada]], [[Government of Canada]] |accessdate= 2014-01-26|date= 2012-11-29 }}</ref>\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Judy Foote]]\n* [[Vishal Dhankhar]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Canadian government scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Canadian industrial research and development organizations]]\n* [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport]]\n* [[Canadian university scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Higher education in Ontario]]\n* [[List of colleges in Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.lambton.on.ca/ Lambton College}}\n{{Commons}}\n\n{{Ont post-secondary|c}}\n\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Colleges in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Education in Sarnia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lambton County]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2014}}\n{{Advert|date=January 2014}}\n}}\n{{Coord|42|58|49.89|N|82|20|54.91|W|display=title|type:edu}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name = '''Lambton College of Applied Arts and Technology'''\n|image = Lambton College.png\n|image_size = 300px\n|motto = Connect\n|president = Judith Morris, President & CEO<ref name= \"Booth20111214\">{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 14 December 2011 |title= Judith Morris gets Lambton College top job, replacing retiring Tony Hanlon |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/judith-morris-gets-lambton-college-top-job-replacing-retiring-tony-hanlon/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\n|type = Public \n|undergrad    = \n|postgrad     = \n|established = 1969\n|city = [[Sarnia]],<br/>[[Mississauga]] and <br/>[[Toronto]]\n|state = [[Ontario]]\n|country = [[Canada]]\n|colours = [[White (color)|White]] and [[Blue (Colour)|Blue]]  {{color box|#00502F}} {{color box|#072B61}} |\n|students =  over 3,500 full-time, over 6,500 part-time, 500 international (on campus), over 3,500 international (off shore), 600 apprenticeship<ref name= \"Booth20111214\"/><ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.studycanada.ca/english/school_profile.php?SchoolID=127 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015091135/http://www.studycanada.ca/english/school_profile.php?SchoolID=127 |archivedate=October 15, 2008 }}{{Failed verification|date=January 2014}}<!-- information not on archived version of webpage --></ref>\n|publictransit   = \n|campus = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n|free_label   = Sports teams\n|free         = Lambton Lions\n|mascot = Pounce\n|affiliations   =  [[Canadian Colleges Athletic Association|CCAA]], [[Association of Canadian Community Colleges|ACCC]], [[Association of Universities and Colleges of Canada|AUCC]], [[Canadian Bureau for International Education|CBIE]]\n|website = http://www.lambtoncollege.ca\n}}\n'''Lambton College''' is a publicly funded college in [[Sarnia]], [[Ontario]], Canada with approximately 3,500 full-time students, 6,500 part-time students and 3,500 international students worldwide. Lambton College also has campuses in [[Mississauga]] and [[Toronto]].<ref name= \"Booth20111214\"/>\n\n==Programs==\nLambton College has more than 90{{quantify|date=January 2014}} post-secondary programs and apprenticeships, academic upgrading, post-graduate, part-time and training programs. The college also has pathways that lead to credentialing.{{clarify|date=January 2014}}\n\nAcademic Schools:\n* School of Technology & Trades\n* School of Business & International Education\n* School of Health, Community Services & Creative Design\n* School of Fire Sciences\n* School of Information Technology\n* Online Education\n\n==Buildings and features==\nThe NOVA Chemicals Health & Research Centre was officially opened in May 2019. The facility is home to all Health Sciences programming labs and advanced technology simulation facilities. The Athletics & Fitness Complex opened in October 2018, and has a 15,000 sq. ft. double gymnasium with seating for 1,241 fans.\n\nCentre of Excellence in Energy & Bio-Industrial Technologies was designed to bring together academic programming, industry-standard training, and research labs. The official opening took place in September 2018 after a two-year, $14.2 million upgrade of the 34,000 sq. ft. facility, which also included the addition of 7,000 sq. ft. of training space.\n\nCreations Fine Dining is an on-campus restaurant and is an applied learning environment for the Hospitality & Tourism Management and Culinary Management programs.<ref name= \"Booth20110224\">{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 24 February 2011 |title= It's no accident: Lambton College works hard to attract new students |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/its-no-accident-lambton-college-works-hard-to-attract-new-students/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe Early Childhood Education Centre is a college training facility used by the Early Childhood Education program. It hosts Ontario Early Years Centre, now known as EarlyON. It is scheduled to close in July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tyler |last= Kula |date= 13 November 2013 |title= Lambton College's Early Childhood Education Centre set to close by July, 2014 |newspaper= [[Sarnia Observer]] |url= http://www.theobserver.ca/2013/11/13/lambton-colleges-early-childhood-education-centre-set-to-close-by-july-2014 |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nFormerly known as the Fire & Public Safety Centre of Excellence, the campus was rebranded as The Fire School in spring 2019. It is an $11-million facility featuring a two-story structure with classrooms, a triple-truck bay, a fire tower and training props.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 3 December 2011 |title= Lambton College celebrates grand opening of new Fire and Public Safety Centre of Excellence |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-celebrates-grand-opening-of-new-fire-and-public-safety-centre-of-excellence/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe Skilled Trades Training Centre provides skilled trades and apprenticeship training with classrooms, and labs and facilities.<ref>{{cite web |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 9 December 2011 |title= Lambton College state of the art labs gives grad leg-up on career in trades |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-state-of-the-art-labs-gives-grad-leg-up-on-career-in-trades/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe Sustainable Smart Home is a $1.2 million building, featuring a cutting-edge energy management system, used for applied research and learning.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 24 June 2011 |title= Sustainable Smart Home opens at Lambton College |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/sustainable-smart-home-opens-at-lambton-college/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\nThe SPA at Lambton is a teaching facility and a full-service spa, the spa is run and managed by students in Lambton's Esthetician and Hairstylist programs.<ref name= \"Booth20110224\"/>\n\n==Student life==\nLambton's Residence houses over 280 students and is located on campus. It includes a courtyard and a student lounge.\nEsports Arena on campus was the first of its kind at a Canadian college.\nThe new Athletics & Fitness Complex features a brand new Fitness Room that is free for students.\nEnactus Lambton is a student group, formed in early 2012, and were crowned World Champions at the 2018 Enactus World Cup, which took place in San Jose, California.\nThe Lambton College team competed with 30 other international college and university teams before the finals where they faced Egypt, India, and Morocco. They're the first Canadian College to ever take home the top prize.\n\n==History==\nIn 1966, Lambton College was the second college in the Ontario college system to officially open. At this time 45 students were enrolled in five programs at the college. The main campus' cornerstone was dedicated on June 4, 1970. The cornerstone is a [[time capsule]] containing coins, bills, stamps, the college calendar for 1970\u201371, a copy of the school's charter, the school seal, a copy of the land deed for the college among other items.\nThe first president of Lambton College was Wolfgang Franke. He started full-time duties in January 1967 and his starting salary was $18,000. The first faculty tour of the original site was delayed because the building housing the classrooms was locked and no one had the key. Faculty member Ron Lawrence discovered (much to his dismay) that his house key fit the lock.\nIn 1975 a sculpture commissioned by the school, ''[[Homage (sculpture)|Homage]]'', was constructed by artist [[Haydn Llewellyn Davies|Haydn Davies]]. The college destroyed the sculpture in 2005. The destruction of the sculpture has been controversial and was the subject of a lawsuit settled in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |first= James |last= Adams |title= College and sculptor resolve dispute over destroyed art |date= 23 August 2012 |origyear= 22 May 2010 |url= https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/college-and-sculptor-resolve-dispute-over-destroyed-art/article4319964/ |newspaper= [[The Globe and Mail]] |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\"Alfoldy2012\">{{cite book |last= Alfoldy |first= Sandra |title= Allied Arts: Architecture and Craft in Postwar Canada |year= 2012 |publisher= McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP |isbn= 9780773539600 |pages= [https://books.google.com/books?id=4dUBJv6Rn_AC&pg=PA83 82\u20134] |chapter= Chapter 3: Scale and Form}}</ref>\n\n==International==\nLambton's international programming began in 1996 with an initiative in China.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |title= Lambton's international flavour no accident for academic strategists looking to the future |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambtons-international-flavour-no-accident-for-academic-strategists-looking-to-the-future/ |date= 13 May 2011 |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref> The international department at Lambton now includes campuses in China, Nigeria and Saudi Arabia and there are between 380 and 500 international students on-campus and 3,500 at international campuses.<ref name= \"Booth20111214\"/><ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 17 July 2011 |title= Lambton College making its global mark |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-making-its-global-mark/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref>\n\n==Scholarships and bursaries==\nLambton College offers a variety of scholarships and bursaries.<ref>{{cite news |first= JD |last= Booth |date= 21 November 2011 |title= Lambton College scholarships total nearly $85k this year |url= http://www.lambtonshield.com/lambton-college-scholarships-total-nearly-85k-this-year/ |newspaper= LambtonShield.com |accessdate= 2014-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mylambton.ca/financial_aid/home |title= Financial Aid Home |work= mylambton.ca}}</ref> Lambton College scholarships for [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]], [[First Nations]] and [[M\u00e9tis]] students include: Aboriginal Post Secondary Education & Training Bursary.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/eng/4078514441563/4078514441563?sb=bn&q=Lambton+College&bp=&fs=000&ag=000&srcDC=10 |title= Aboriginal Post Secondary Education & Training Bursary: Lambton College |publisher= [[Aboriginal Affairs and Northern Development Canada]], [[Government of Canada]] |accessdate= 2014-01-26|date= 2012-11-29 }}</ref>\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Judy Foote]]\n* [[Vishal Dhankhar]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Canadian government scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Canadian industrial research and development organizations]]\n* [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport]]\n* [[Canadian university scientific research organizations]]\n* [[Higher education in Ontario]]\n* [[List of colleges in Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.lambton.on.ca/ Lambton College}}\n{{Commons}}\n\n{{Ont post-secondary|c}}\n\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Colleges in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Education in Sarnia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lambton County]]\n", "name_user": "Red dwarf", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lambton_College"}
{"title_page": "Kabukich\u014d, Tokyo", "text_new": "{{short description|Town located in Shinjuku-ku, Tokyo}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2006}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = {{raise|0.2em|Kabukich\u014d}}\n| native_name             = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|ja|\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a}}}}}}\n| native_name_lang        = ja\n| settlement_type         = Entertainment and [[red-light district]]\n| image_skyline           = Kabukicho red gate and colorful neon street signs at night, Shinjuku, Tokyo, Japan.jpg\n| image_alt               = Red lighted gate denoting entrance to Kabukich\u014d, a district in Shinjuku-ku, Tokyo. Colorful neon signs for businesses line both sides of the street.\n| image_caption           = Kabukich\u014d Ichiban-gai gate and colorful neon street signs\n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| etymology               = \n| nickname                = Sleepless Town ({{nihongo2|\u7720\u3089\u306a\u3044\u8857}})\n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Japan Tokyo city#Japan Tokyo#Japan\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| coordinates             = {{Coord|35.69388|N|139.703422|E|source:dewiki_region:JP-13_type:city|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Japan]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[List of regions of Japan|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kant\u014d region|Kant\u014d]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Prefectures of Japan|Prefecture]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Tokyo]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Special wards of Tokyo|Special ward]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Shinjuku]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| leader_title3           = \n| leader_name3            = \n| leader_title4           = \n| leader_name4            = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- hectares -->\n| area_total_ha           = 36\n| area_land_ha            = \n| area_water_ha           = \n| area_urban_ha           = \n| area_rural_ha           = \n| area_metro_ha           = \n| area_blank1_ha          = \n| area_blank2_ha          = \n| length_km               = \n| width_km                = \n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_total        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| population_demonym      = \n| timezone1               = [[Japan Standard Time]]\n| utc_offset1             = +9\n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = {{URL|www.kabukicho.or.jp}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Kabukich\u014d'''|\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a}} is an entertainment and [[red-light district]] in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]], Japan. Kabukich\u014d is the location of many [[host and hostess clubs]], [[love hotel]]s, shops, restaurants, and nightclubs, and is often called the \"Sleepless Town\" (\u7720\u3089\u306a\u3044\u8857).  [[Shinjuku Golden Gai]], famous for plethora of small bars, is part of Kabukicho.\n\nThe district's name comes from late-1940s plans to build a [[kabuki]] theater; although the theater was never built, the name stuck.\n\nThe area has many movie theaters, and is located near [[Shinjuku Station]], [[Seibu Shinjuku Station]], and several other major railway and subway stations.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Kabukicho cropped GSI CKT20092-C62-15 20090427.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial photograph (2009)]]\nOriginally, the area was known as {{nihongo|'''Tsunohazu'''|\u89d2\u7b48}} and was a swamp. After the [[Meiji Period]], the area became a duck sanctuary. As the Yodobashi Purification Plant was built in 1893, the ponds were filled in. In 1920, a girls' school was built there, and the surroundings were developed into a residential area. Prior to [[World War II]], the district was one of the areas open to foreign-born property owners (primarily from Taiwan and Korea), who mainly operated ''tsurekomi yado'', predecessors to today's [[love hotel]]s.<ref name=JT-2002/>\n\nDuring the war, a [[Bombing of Tokyo in World War II|bombing raid]] on April 13, 1945, razed the area to the ground.<ref name=JT-2002/> After the war, Kihei Suzuki from the Association of Readjustment and Reconstruction of Shinjuku worked with the major landowner, Mohei Minejima to draw up plans for Kiku-za, a kabuki theatre, in the area; they believed that performers from the [[Kabuki-za]] theatre in Ginza would accept their invitation to perform at Kiku-za.<ref name=JT-2002/> As a result, Hideaki Ishikawa, a regional planner,  dubbed the town Kabukich\u014d, which was adopted on April 1, 1948. Although the theatre was cancelled due to financial problems, the name remained. The {{ill|Tokyu Cultural Hall|ja|\u6771\u6025\u6587\u5316\u4f1a\u9928}} (to the south, in Shibuya), {{ill|Tokyu Milano-za|ja|\u65b0\u5bbfTOKYU MILANO}} movie theater, Tokyo Ice Skating Rink, and [[Shinjuku Koma Theater]] were all completed in 1956, cementing the area's reputation as an entertainment center.<ref name=K'cho-history>{{cite web |url=http://www.kabukicho.or.jp/history.php?lang=en |title=A City represent its people: A History of Kabukicho |website=kabukicho.or.jp |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nKabukich\u014d was quickly redeveloped after the war, mainly due to the efforts of the [[Chinese in Japan|overseas Chinese in Japan]] who bought land left unused after the expos and greatly developed them. The \"three most renowned overseas Chinese of Kabukicho\" include the founder of [[Humax]], [[Lin Yi-wen]], who started his business with a [[cabaret]]; Lin Tsai-wang, who built the F\u016brin Kaikan; and Lee Ho-chu, owner of the Tokyo Hotel Chinese restaurant.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.cw.com.tw/article/article.action?id=2303 |title=Tokyo's Kabukicho - City of the Taiwanese |author=Tsuyoshi, Nojima |publisher=CommonWealth |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> In 2002, it was estimated that 70% of the land in Kabukich\u014d was owned by foreign-born Japanese residents and their descendants.<ref name=JT-2002/> The rise of home video entertainment decreased the demand for live performances and film theaters, and Kabukich\u014d became home to a number of video arcades, discos, and ''fuzoku'' (businesses offering sexual services).<ref name=JT-2015/>\n\n{{ill|Watanabe Katsumi|ja|\u6e21\u8fba\u514b\u5df3}}, a freelance portrait photographer who took pictures and sold prints back to his subjects for a modest {{JPY|200}}, documented the citizens of Kabukich\u014d during this transition period in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theweek.com/captured/547903/tokyo-demimonde |title=Tokyo demimonde |author=Spaeth, Ryu |date=2015 |work=The Week |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.messynessychic.com/2019/03/28/an-insider-peep-into-tokyos-secretive-red-light-district-then-now/ |title=An Insider Peep into Tokyo's Secretive Red Light District: Then & Now |author=Knapp, Rancky |date=March 28, 2019 |website=Messy Nessy Chic |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> Katsumi had apprenticed to a portrait studio in Tokyo shortly after moving there in 1962; he took his [[street photography]] portraits at night using a strobe as a side job.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/716644 |title=Untitled |author=Katsumi, Watanabe |date=1967 |website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.takaishiigallery.com/en/archives/16345/ |title=Katsumi Watanabe 'Shinjuku' |date=September 2015 |publisher=Taka Ishii Gallery |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> In 1971, {{ill|Takeshi Aida|ja|\u611b\u7530\u6b66}}, a former mattress salesman, opened \"Club Ai\",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/sep/18/japan.justinmccurry |title=Tokyo plays host to sexual shift |author=McCurry, Justin |date=17 September 2004 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> the first [[Host and hostess clubs|host club]] in Kabukich\u014d; at its peak, Aida's company reported {{JPY|2.7}}&nbsp;billion in annual revenue.<ref name=JT-2015/>\n\n{{multiple image\n|direction=vertical |align=right\n\n|image1=\u65b0\u5bbf \u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a Shinjuku Tokyo, Japan Sigma 35mm Canon 6D (33795009235).jpg\n|caption1=Night (2016)\n\n|image2=Kabukicho (31465119364).jpg\n|caption2=Day (2016)\n\n|footer=Kabukich\u014d, view north along Ichibangai-dori towards the Humax Pavilion complex}}\nBy 1999, the area had been named \"Asia's largest adult entertainment district\", and tabloids were regularly running candid photographs of drunken Kabukich\u014d patrons fighting and being arrested.<ref name=JT-2015/> However, starting in 2003, joint citizen and police patrols began enforcing business licensing,<ref name=JT-2004/> and the 1948 [[Businesses Affecting Public Morals Regulation Act]] was more strictly enforced as well starting in April 2004, forcing adult-themed businesses to start removing customers at midnight in preparation to close by 1&nbsp;AM. Kabukich\u014d leaders attributed the change in enforcement to Tokyo Governor [[Shintaro Ishihara]] and the [[Tokyo bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=JT-2008/><ref name=TR-2008/>\n\nAt present, the {{convert|36|ha|acre sqmi|abbr=on}} Kabukich\u014d district<ref name=JT-2015>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/05/23/national/media-national/changing-face-tokyos-red-light-district/ |url-access=limited |title=The changing face of Tokyo's 'red-light' district |author=Schreiber, Mark |date=May 23, 2015 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> has transformed from a residential area to a world-famous red-light district housing over three thousand bars, nightclubs, love hotels, massage parlours, hostess clubs and the like. Although referred here as a \"red light district\", there are no red lights in the literal sense with prostitutes in the windows [[De Wallen|as in Amsterdam]].\n\nRecently, tourism from China and Korea is on the rise, and so, many tourists can be seen in Kabukich\u014d even during daytime. After several large hotels opened in the district, the Kabukicho Concierge Association was formed to recommend businesses that would be safe for foreign patrons, as the area is notorious for the practice known as ''bottakuri'', where some businesses add exorbitant [[hidden fees]] to bring the final bill well beyond the initial advertised prices.<ref name=JT-2015/>\n\n==Geography and statistics==\n{{OSM Location map\n |coord={{Coord|35.695|139.7035}}\n |float=left\n |zoom=16\n |width=400 |height=400\n |scalemark=20\n |shape1=n-square\n |shape-color1=#f00\n |shape-outline1=#fff\n |mark-size1=20\n |mark-coord1 ={{Coord|35.693822|139.701023}}\n |mark-title1 =Red \"Ichiban-gai Gate\" entrance\n |mark-coord2 ={{Coord|35.695390|139.700011}} |shape-color2=#00f |shape2=n-circle\n |mark-title2 =[[Seibu-Shinjuku Station]]\n |mark-coord3 ={{Coord|35.695560|139.701228}} |shape-color3=#080\n |mark-title3 =[[Cinecity Square]]\n |mark-coord4 ={{Coord|35.696411|139.701378}} |shape4=n-cross\n |mark-title4 =Ohkubo Hospital\n |mark-coord5 ={{Coord|35.697429|139.701309}} |shape-color5=#080\n |mark-title5 =[[\u014ckubo Park]]\n |mark-coord6 ={{Coord|35.693760|139.701731}}\n |mark-title6 =[[Don Quijote (store)]]\n |mark-coord7 ={{Coord|35.695122|139.701972}}\n |mark-title7 =[[Godzilla head]] / [[Toho Cinemas]]\n |mark-coord8 ={{coord|35.694378|139.702849}}\n |mark-title8 =Robot Restaurant\n |mark-coord9 ={{Coord|35|41|38|N|139|42|17|E}}\n |mark-title9 =[[Shinjuku Golden Gai]]\n |mark-coord10={{Coord|35|41|37|N|139|42|19|E}}\n |mark-title10=[[Hanazono Shrine]]\n |mark-coord11={{coord|35.692229|139.700910}} |shape-color11=#00f |shape11=n-circle\n |mark-title11=[[Shinjuku Station]], East Exit\n |fullscreen-option=1\n |caption=Selected locations in and near Kabukich\u014d,&nbsp;Shinjuku,&nbsp;Tokyo {{flatlist|style=font-size:small;|\n* {{color box|#f00|Points&nbsp;of&nbsp;interest|#fff|border=#f00}}\n* {{color box|#00f|Transportation|border=#00f}}\n* {{color box|#080|Parks&nbsp;and&nbsp;open&nbsp;spaces|#fff|border=#0f0}}\n}}\n |auto-caption=1\n}}\nKabukicho is generally bounded by:\n* Railroad tracks (on the west)\n* {{nihongo|\u9756\u56fd\u901a\u308a|Yasukuni-D\u014dri}} (on the south)\n* {{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Route 305|ja|\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u9053305\u53f7\u829d\u65b0\u5bbf\u738b\u5b50\u7dda}} ({{nihongo|\u660e\u6cbb\u901a\u308a|Meiji-D\u014dri}}, on the east)\n* {{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Route 302|ja|\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u9053302\u53f7\u65b0\u5bbf\u4e21\u56fd\u7dda}} ({{nihongo|\u8077\u5b89\u901a\u308a|Shokuan-D\u014dri}}, on the north)\n\n===Notable locations===\nThe red {{nihongo|\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a\u4e00\u756a\u8857|Kabukich\u014d Ichiban-gai}} gate, near the southwest corner along Yasukuni-D\u014dri, is often photographed as the main entrance to Kabukich\u014d. Other major entrances, east of Ichibangai-Dori along Yasukuni-Dori, include {{nihongo|\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u30e9\u30eb\u30ed\u30fc\u30c9|Sentoraru R\u014ddo|Central Road}}, where the Kabukich\u014d branch of [[Don Quijote]] is; and another neon-lit arch at {{nihongo|\u3055\u304f\u3089\u901a\u308a|Sakura-D\u014dri}}.\n\nThe Shinjuku Koma Theater was a landmark in Kabukich\u014d. By 2008, it had moved to its third location; since it opened in 1956, it has hosted concerts and other performances by top stars, including ''[[enka]]'' singers [[Sabur\u014d Kitajima]], [[Kiyoshi Hikawa]], and actor [[Ken Matsudaira]]. The management announced that they would close after the December 31, 2008 show, and the building was demolished in 2009.<ref>[http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/trend/080528/trd0805281851009-n1.htm \u300c\u6f14\u6b4c\u306e\u6bbf\u5802\u300d\u65b0\u5bbf\u30b3\u30de\u3001\u4eca\u5e74\u9650\u308a\u3067\u9589\u9928 (1/2\u30da\u30fc\u30b8) - MSN\u7523\u7d4c\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9] [\"Enka's Hall of Fame\" Shinjuku Koma, closed only for this year] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531011228/http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/trend/080528/trd0805281851009-n1.htm |date=2008-05-31 }} (Retrieved May 28, 2008)</ref> The site was redeveloped and the Toho Shinjuku Building was completed there in 2014, including the 12-screen [[Toho Cinemas]] Shinjuku theatre and the Hotel Gracery Shinjuku. A \"life-size\" [[Godzilla head|replica]] of [[Godzilla]] (from the neck up) was added to an outdoor terrace in 2015; it has since become a local landmark.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tokyoreporter.com/japan-news/national/godzilla-to-receive-shinjuku-residency/ |title=Godzilla to receive Shinjuku 'residency' |date=April 5, 2015 |work=Tokyo Reporter |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Tokyu Milano-za movie theater, just west of Cinecity Square, was the largest in Japan when it opened in 1956.<ref name=K'cho-history/> Its last day of operation was December 31, 2014, closing after a screening of the film ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.alamy.com/tokyo-japan-fans-throng-the-shinjuku-milano-za-movie-theater-in-tokyos-image151340061.html |title=Fans throng the Shinjuku Milano-za movie theater in Tokyo's Shinjuku Ward on Dec. 31, 2014, the last day of its operation, to see the American film \"E.T.,\" chosen for the last screening. The movie theater, one of the largest in Japan with 1,064 seats, opened in December 1956. |author=Warnick, BJ |date=31 December 2014 |agency=Newscom |work=Alamy |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref> A {{convert|225|m|adj=on}} high skyscraper is planned to be built on the site.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://japan-forward.com/shinjuku-tokyu-milano-promises-new-ways-to-enjoy-kabuki-cho-nightlife-come-2022/ |title=Shinjuku Tokyu Milano Promises New Ways to Enjoy Kabuki-cho Nightlife Come 2022 |author=Okada, Mizuki |date=August 14, 2019 |work=Japan Forward |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Crime==\nIn 2004, according to a spokesperson of Metropolitan Tokyo, there were more than 1,000 [[yakuza]] members in Kabukich\u014d, and 120 different enterprises under their control.<ref name=\"yakuza\">2004\u5e741\u670819\u65e5\u7af9\u82b1\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u526f\u77e5\u4e8b\u767a\u8a00\u30fb\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a\u4f4f\u6c11\u3068\u306e\u61c7\u8ac7\u4f1a</ref>{{full|date=June 2015}}\n\nEntering the new millennium, laws were more strictly enforced and patrols became more frequent. In addition, fifty [[closed-circuit camera]]s were installed in May 2002 after the [[Myojo 56 building fire]] that killed 44;<ref name=JT-2002>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2002/01/20/general/kabukicho-where-worlds-collide/ |title=Kabukicho: where worlds collide |author=Schreiber, Mark |url-access=limited |date=January 20, 2002 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=JT-2008>{{cite news |url=https://japantoday.com/category/features/lifestyle/last-call-for-kabukicho-red-light-district?comment-order=latest |title=Last call for Kabukicho red-light district |author=Bull, Brett |date=December 22, 2008 |newspaper=Japan Today |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2001/09/04/national/gas-pipes-ruled-out-as-cause-of-kabukicho-blaze/ |url-access=limited |title=Gas pipes ruled out as cause of Kabukicho blaze |date= September 4, 2001 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref> the patrols and cameras reduced criminal activities in Kabukich\u014d, amidst controversy.<ref name=TR-2008>{{cite news |url=https://www.tokyoreporter.com/japan-news/special-reports/kabukicho-comes-clean/ |title=Kabukicho comes clean |date=May 2, 2008 |work=Tokyo Reporter |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrivate citizens and government agencies launched a joint effort in July 2003, called the Shinjuku Shopping Center Committee to Expel Organized-Crime Groups, with the aim to replace unlicensed and adult-oriented businesses (which were believed to pay [[protection fees]] to organized crime groups) with legitimate businesses.<ref name=JT-2004>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2004/06/13/people/cops-and-citizens-bid-to-blitz-street-sleaze/ |url-access=limited |title=Cops and citizens bid to blitz street sleaze |author=Prideaux, Eric |date=June 13, 2004 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> In 2004, the police undertook an operation clamping down on illegal clubs and [[brothel]]s, causing many to go out of business. An amendment to the 1948 Adult Entertainment law made aggressive catching of female patrons by male hosts illegal.<ref name=TR-2008/> Also, the Kabukich\u014d Renaissance organization started in April 2008 to rid Kabukich\u014d of the yakuza; office manager Yoshihisa Shimoda stated \"[a]t the end of the day, we want Kabukicho to be clean. We want security, safety and a pleasant environment.\"<ref name=JT-2008/>\n\nIn 2011, Tokyo began to enforce the Organised Crime Exclusion Ordinance, which makes it a crime for businesses or individuals to deal with the Yakuza.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2012/08/201282115458449808.html |title=Meeting Japan's yakuza |author=Chou, Chan Tau |date=23 August 2012 |work=Al Jazeera |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> Although the punishment for violating the ordinance ranges up to one year in prison and a fine of {{JPY|50000}}, it is intended to provide an excuse for refusing to make protection payments.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/11/02/national/media-national/illegal-pay-gangs-thats-not-point/ |url-access=limited |title=It's illegal to pay gangs ... but that's not the point |author=Adelstein, Jake |date=November 2, 2019 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Host Clubs and Cabaret Club at Kabuki-ch\u014d, Shinjuku (2016-07-13 15.32.28 by Dick Thomas Johnson).jpg|thumb|right|Advertisements for host, hostess, and cabaret clubs (2016)]]\n===''Bottakuri''===\n''Bottakuri'' is a form of [[bait-and-switch]], where patrons are attracted by a low advertised price but then charged numerous hidden fees. In one instance, a group of nine was lured into a bar under the promise the all-inclusive cost was {{JPY|4000}}; the hostesses inside consumed 172 drinks and the final bill was {{JPY|2663000}}. The staff at the bar allegedly threatened the patrons to ensure payment. In 2015, there were 1,052 reported cases of ''bottakuri'' in the first four months of the year alone, particularly targeting foreign tourists from China and Korea,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/06/17/national/crime-legal/one-kabukicho-bar-allegedly-ripped-drinkers/ |url-access=limited |title=How one Kabukicho bar allegedly ripped off its drinkers |author=Kodera, Atsushi |date=June 17, 2015 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> prompting a crackdown that began in May; in July, there were only 45 reported cases of ''bottakuri'' and 28 bars had been shut down.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/08/12/national/crime-legal/police-crackdown-curbing-extortionist-kabukicho-bottakuri-bar-rip-offs/ |url-access=limited |title=Police crackdown curbing extortionist Kabukicho 'bottakuri' bar rip-offs |agency=Kyodo |date=August 12, 2015 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Aida founded the Shinjuku Kabukicho Host Club Anti-Organized Crime Gang Association to disassociate host and hostess clubs from organized crime, reduce the aggressive \"catching\" street solicitations, and eliminate the ''bottakuri'' practice.<ref name=TR-2008/>\n\n==In media==\nKabukich\u014d has been featured in:\n* [[Yakuza (video game)|''Yakuza'']] (video game), as Kamurocho<ref>{{cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/how-yakuzas-city-changes-from-game-to-game-1821884988 |title=How ''Yakuza''{{'}}s City Changes From Game To Game |author=Alexandra, Heather |date=8 January 2018 |work=Kotaku |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n* ''[[Gin Tama]]'' (manga)\n* ''[[City Hunter]]'' (manga)\n* ''[[Tokyo Vice]]'' (2009 memoir by [[Jake Adelstein]])\n* ''[[Shin Petshop of Horrors]]'' (manga) <ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pet_Shop_of_Horrors</ref>\n* ''[[Weathering with You]]'' (film)<ref>{{cite web|last=Salupen|first=Mark|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/10/01/films/the-real-tokyo-locations-from-makoto-shinkais-anime-movies/|title=The real Tokyo locations from Makoto Shinkai's anime movies|newspaper=[[The Japan Times]]|date=1 October 2019|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Case File n\u00ba221: Kabukicho]] (anime television series)\n{{clear}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Shinjuku Theatre+Shinjuku Koma Feb1960.jpg|Shinjuku Koma, looking north from the east end of Cinecity Square (Feb 1960)\nFile:Tokyo Shinjuku Milano za.jpg|Tokyu Milano-za (2012), looking west from Cinecity Square\nFile:Central Road Kabukicho-Sinjyuku-Tokyo.jpg|Kabukich\u014d, view north along Central toward Toho Building\nFile:Shinjuku Toho1.jpg|Shinjuku Toho Building\nFile:Tokyo Route 302 -06.jpg|View east along Yasukuni-Dori, the southern border of Kabukich\u014d.\nFile:Kabukicho-Shinjuku-Tokyo 20120204.jpg|View east along Yasukuni-Dori at night.\nFile:I love Kabukicho (29262192243).jpg|I \u2665 Kabuki-ch\u014d sign.\nFile:Sakura Dori street Kabukicho-Sinjyuku-Tokyo.jpg|Gate at Sakura-Dori, looking north from Yasukuni-Dori\nFile:Shinjuku 06.JPG|Prominent signs along Sakura-Dori (\u3055\u304f\u3089\u901a\u308a), including entrance to Robot Restaurant\nFile:Charge of the fembots Robot Restaurant, Shinjuku Tokyo.jpg|Show at Robot Restaurant\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tokyo}}\n* [[J\u016bs\u014d]], Osaka\n* [[Kyabakura Union]]\n* [[Tobita Shinchi]], [[Osaka]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Kabukich\u014d, Tokyo}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100804074445/http://www.d-kabukicho.com/en/ Kabukicho Renaissance official website] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.kabukicho.or.jp/ KABUKI\u753a Kabukicho portal site] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091012040720/http://kabukicho-commune.jp/ Kabukicho Commune] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Neighborhoods of Tokyo}}\n{{Prostitution in Japan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kabukicho, Tokyo}}\n[[Category:Neighborhoods of Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Red-light districts in Japan]]\n[[Category:Shinjuku]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Town located in Shinjuku-ku, Tokyo}}\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2006}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = {{raise|0.2em|Kabukich\u014d}}\n| native_name             = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|ja|\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a}}}}}}\n| native_name_lang        = ja\n| settlement_type         = Entertainment and [[red-light district]]\n| image_skyline           = Kabukicho red gate and colorful neon street signs at night, Shinjuku, Tokyo, Japan.jpg\n| image_alt               = Red lighted gate denoting entrance to Kabukich\u014d, a district in Shinjuku-ku, Tokyo. Colorful neon signs for businesses line both sides of the street.\n| image_caption           = Kabukich\u014d Ichiban-gai gate and colorful neon street signs\n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| etymology               = \n| nickname                = Sleepless Town ({{nihongo2|\u7720\u3089\u306a\u3044\u8857}})\n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = Japan Tokyo city#Japan Tokyo#Japan\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| coordinates             = {{Coord|35.69388|N|139.703422|E|source:dewiki_region:JP-13_type:city|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Japan]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[List of regions of Japan|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Kant\u014d region|Kant\u014d]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Prefectures of Japan|Prefecture]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Tokyo]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Special wards of Tokyo|Special ward]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Shinjuku]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| leader_title3           = \n| leader_name3            = \n| leader_title4           = \n| leader_name4            = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- hectares -->\n| area_total_ha           = 36\n| area_land_ha            = \n| area_water_ha           = \n| area_urban_ha           = \n| area_rural_ha           = \n| area_metro_ha           = \n| area_blank1_ha          = \n| area_blank2_ha          = \n| length_km               = \n| width_km                = \n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_total        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| population_demonym      = \n| timezone1               = [[Japan Standard Time]]\n| utc_offset1             = +9\n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = {{URL|www.kabukicho.or.jp}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Kabukich\u014d'''|\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a}} is an entertainment and [[red-light district]] in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]], Japan. Kabukich\u014d is the location of many [[host and hostess clubs]], [[love hotel]]s, shops, restaurants, and nightclubs, and is often called the \"Sleepless Town\" (\u7720\u3089\u306a\u3044\u8857).  [[Shinjuku Golden Gai]], famous for plethora of small bars, is part of Kabukicho.\n\nThe district's name comes from late-1940s plans to build a [[kabuki]] theater; although the theater was never built, the name stuck.\n\nThe area has many movie theaters, and is located near [[Shinjuku Station]], [[Seibu Shinjuku Station]], and several other major railway and subway stations.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Kabukicho cropped GSI CKT20092-C62-15 20090427.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial photograph (2009)]]\nOriginally, the area was known as {{nihongo|'''Tsunohazu'''|\u89d2\u7b48}} and was a swamp. After the [[Meiji Period]], the area became a duck sanctuary. As the Yodobashi Purification Plant was built in 1893, the ponds were filled in. In 1920, a girls' school was built there, and the surroundings were developed into a residential area. Prior to [[World War II]], the district was one of the areas open to foreign-born property owners (primarily from Taiwan and Korea), who mainly operated ''tsurekomi yado'', predecessors to today's [[love hotel]]s.<ref name=JT-2002/>\n\nDuring the war, a [[Bombing of Tokyo in World War II|bombing raid]] on April 13, 1945, razed the area to the ground.<ref name=JT-2002/> After the war, Kihei Suzuki from the Association of Readjustment and Reconstruction of Shinjuku worked with the major landowner, Mohei Minejima to draw up plans for Kiku-za, a kabuki theatre, in the area; they believed that performers from the [[Kabuki-za]] theatre in Ginza would accept their invitation to perform at Kiku-za.<ref name=JT-2002/> As a result, Hideaki Ishikawa, a regional planner,  dubbed the town Kabukich\u014d, which was adopted on April 1, 1948. Although the theatre was cancelled due to financial problems, the name remained. The {{ill|Tokyu Cultural Hall|ja|\u6771\u6025\u6587\u5316\u4f1a\u9928}} (to the south, in Shibuya), {{ill|Tokyu Milano-za|ja|\u65b0\u5bbfTOKYU MILANO}} movie theater, Tokyo Ice Skating Rink, and [[Shinjuku Koma Theater]] were all completed in 1956, cementing the area's reputation as an entertainment center.<ref name=K'cho-history>{{cite web |url=http://www.kabukicho.or.jp/history.php?lang=en |title=A City represent its people: A History of Kabukicho |website=kabukicho.or.jp |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nKabukich\u014d was quickly redeveloped after the war, mainly due to the efforts of the [[Chinese in Japan|overseas Chinese in Japan]] who bought land left unused after the expos and greatly developed them. The \"three most renowned overseas Chinese of Kabukicho\" include the founder of [[Humax]], [[Lin Yi-wen]], who started his business with a [[cabaret]]; Lin Tsai-wang, who built the F\u016brin Kaikan; and Lee Ho-chu, owner of the Tokyo Hotel Chinese restaurant.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.cw.com.tw/article/article.action?id=2303 |title=Tokyo's Kabukicho - City of the Taiwanese |author=Tsuyoshi, Nojima |publisher=CommonWealth |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> In 2002, it was estimated that 70% of the land in Kabukich\u014d was owned by foreign-born Japanese residents and their descendants.<ref name=JT-2002/> The rise of home video entertainment decreased the demand for live performances and film theaters, and Kabukich\u014d became home to a number of video arcades, discos, and ''fuzoku'' (businesses offering sexual services).<ref name=JT-2015/>\n\n{{ill|Watanabe Katsumi|ja|\u6e21\u8fba\u514b\u5df3}}, a freelance portrait photographer who took pictures and sold prints back to his subjects for a modest {{JPY|200}}, documented the citizens of Kabukich\u014d during this transition period in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theweek.com/captured/547903/tokyo-demimonde |title=Tokyo demimonde |author=Spaeth, Ryu |date=2015 |work=The Week |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.messynessychic.com/2019/03/28/an-insider-peep-into-tokyos-secretive-red-light-district-then-now/ |title=An Insider Peep into Tokyo's Secretive Red Light District: Then & Now |author=Knapp, Rancky |date=March 28, 2019 |website=Messy Nessy Chic |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> Katsumi had apprenticed to a portrait studio in Tokyo shortly after moving there in 1962; he took his [[street photography]] portraits at night using a strobe as a side job.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/716644 |title=Untitled |author=Katsumi, Watanabe |date=1967 |website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.takaishiigallery.com/en/archives/16345/ |title=Katsumi Watanabe 'Shinjuku' |date=September 2015 |publisher=Taka Ishii Gallery |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> In 1971, {{ill|Takeshi Aida|ja|\u611b\u7530\u6b66}}, a former mattress salesman, opened \"Club Ai\",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/sep/18/japan.justinmccurry |title=Tokyo plays host to sexual shift |author=McCurry, Justin |date=17 September 2004 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=22 November 2019}}</ref> the first [[Host and hostess clubs|host club]] in Kabukich\u014d; at its peak, Aida's company reported {{JPY|2.7}}&nbsp;billion in annual revenue.<ref name=JT-2015/>\n\n{{multiple image\n|direction=vertical |align=right\n\n|image1=\u65b0\u5bbf \u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a Shinjuku Tokyo, Japan Sigma 35mm Canon 6D (33795009235).jpg\n|caption1=Night (2016)\n\n|image2=Kabukicho (31465119364).jpg\n|caption2=Day (2016)\n\n|footer=Kabukich\u014d, view north along Ichibangai-dori towards the Humax Pavilion complex}}\nBy 1999, the area had been named \"Asia's largest adult entertainment district\", and tabloids were regularly running candid photographs of drunken Kabukich\u014d patrons fighting and being arrested.<ref name=JT-2015/> However, starting in 2003, joint citizen and police patrols began enforcing business licensing,<ref name=JT-2004/> and the 1948 [[Businesses Affecting Public Morals Regulation Act]] was more strictly enforced as well starting in April 2004, forcing adult-themed businesses to start removing customers at midnight in preparation to close by 1&nbsp;AM. Kabukich\u014d leaders attributed the change in enforcement to Tokyo Governor [[Shintaro Ishihara]] and the [[Tokyo bid for the 2016 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=JT-2008/><ref name=TR-2008/>\n\nAt present, the {{convert|36|ha|acre sqmi|abbr=on}} Kabukich\u014d district<ref name=JT-2015>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/05/23/national/media-national/changing-face-tokyos-red-light-district/ |url-access=limited |title=The changing face of Tokyo's 'red-light' district |author=Schreiber, Mark |date=May 23, 2015 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> has transformed from a residential area to a world-famous red-light district housing over three thousand bars, nightclubs, love hotels, massage parlours, hostess clubs and the like. Although referred here as a \"red light district\", there are no red lights in the literal sense with prostitutes in the windows [[De Wallen|as in Amsterdam]].\n\nRecently, tourism from China and Korea is on the rise, and so, many tourists can be seen in Kabukich\u014d even during daytime. After several large hotels opened in the district, the Kabukicho Concierge Association was formed to recommend businesses that would be safe for foreign patrons, as the area is notorious for the practice known as ''bottakuri'', where some businesses add exorbitant [[hidden fees]] to bring the final bill well beyond the initial advertised prices.<ref name=JT-2015/>\n\n==Geography and statistics==\n{{OSM Location map\n |coord={{Coord|35.695|139.7035}}\n |float=left\n |zoom=16\n |width=400 |height=400\n |scalemark=20\n |shape1=n-square\n  |shape-color1=#f00\n  |shape-outline1=#fff\n  |mark-size1=20\n |mark-coord1 ={{Coord|35.693822|139.701023}}\n |mark-title1 =Red \"Ichiban-gai Gate\" entrance\n |mark-coord2 ={{Coord|35.695390|139.700011}} |shape-color2=#00f |shape2=n-circle\n |mark-title2 =[[Seibu-Shinjuku Station]]\n |mark-coord3 ={{Coord|35.695560|139.701228}} |shape-color3=#080\n |mark-title3 =[[Cinecity Square]]\n |mark-coord4 ={{Coord|35.696411|139.701378}} |shape4=n-cross\n |mark-title4 =Ohkubo Hospital\n |mark-coord5 ={{Coord|35.697429|139.701309}} |shape-color5=#080\n |mark-title5 =[[\u014ckubo Park]]\n |mark-coord6 ={{Coord|35.693760|139.701731}}\n |mark-title6 =[[Don Quijote (store)]]\n |mark-coord7 ={{Coord|35.695122|139.701972}}\n |mark-title7 =[[Godzilla head]] / [[Toho Cinemas]]\n |mark-coord8 ={{coord|35.694378|139.702849}}\n |mark-title8 =Robot Restaurant\n |mark-coord9 ={{Coord|35|41|38|N|139|42|17|E}}\n |mark-title9 =[[Shinjuku Golden Gai]]\n |mark-coord10={{Coord|35|41|37|N|139|42|19|E}}\n |mark-title10=[[Hanazono Shrine]]\n |mark-coord11={{coord|35.692229|139.700910}} |shape-color11=#00f |shape11=n-circle\n |mark-title11=[[Shinjuku Station]], East Exit\n |fullscreen-option=1\n |caption=Selected locations in and near Kabukich\u014d, Shinjuku, Tokyo&nbsp;<small>{{flatlist|\n* {{color box|#f00|Points of interest|#fff|border=#f00}}\n* {{color box|#080|Parks and open spaces|#fff|border=#0f0}}\n* {{color box|#00f|Transportation|border=#00f}} }}</small>\n |auto-caption=1\n}}\nKabukicho is generally bounded by:\n* Railroad tracks (on the west)\n* {{nihongo|\u9756\u56fd\u901a\u308a|Yasukuni-D\u014dri}} (on the south)\n* {{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Route 305|ja|\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u9053305\u53f7\u829d\u65b0\u5bbf\u738b\u5b50\u7dda}} ({{nihongo|\u660e\u6cbb\u901a\u308a|Meiji-D\u014dri}}, on the east)\n* {{ill|Tokyo Metropolitan Route 302|ja|\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u9053302\u53f7\u65b0\u5bbf\u4e21\u56fd\u7dda}} ({{nihongo|\u8077\u5b89\u901a\u308a|Shokuan-D\u014dri}}, on the north)\n\n===Notable locations===\nThe red {{nihongo|\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a\u4e00\u756a\u8857|Kabukich\u014d Ichiban-gai}} gate, near the southwest corner along Yasukuni-D\u014dri, is often photographed as the main entrance to Kabukich\u014d. Other major entrances, east of Ichibangai-Dori along Yasukuni-Dori, include {{nihongo|\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u30e9\u30eb\u30ed\u30fc\u30c9|Sentoraru R\u014ddo|Central Road}}, where the Kabukich\u014d branch of [[Don Quijote]] is; and another neon-lit arch at {{nihongo|\u3055\u304f\u3089\u901a\u308a|Sakura-D\u014dri}}.\n\nThe Shinjuku Koma Theater was a landmark in Kabukich\u014d. By 2008, it had moved to its third location; since it opened in 1956, it has hosted concerts and other performances by top stars, including ''[[enka]]'' singers [[Sabur\u014d Kitajima]], [[Kiyoshi Hikawa]], and actor [[Ken Matsudaira]]. The management announced that they would close after the December 31, 2008 show, and the building was demolished in 2009.<ref>[http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/trend/080528/trd0805281851009-n1.htm \u300c\u6f14\u6b4c\u306e\u6bbf\u5802\u300d\u65b0\u5bbf\u30b3\u30de\u3001\u4eca\u5e74\u9650\u308a\u3067\u9589\u9928 (1/2\u30da\u30fc\u30b8) - MSN\u7523\u7d4c\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9] [\"Enka's Hall of Fame\" Shinjuku Koma, closed only for this year] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531011228/http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/trend/080528/trd0805281851009-n1.htm |date=2008-05-31 }} (Retrieved May 28, 2008)</ref> The site was redeveloped and the Toho Shinjuku Building was completed there in 2014, including the 12-screen [[Toho Cinemas]] Shinjuku theatre and the Hotel Gracery Shinjuku. A \"life-size\" [[Godzilla head|replica]] of [[Godzilla]] (from the neck up) was added to an outdoor terrace in 2015; it has since become a local landmark.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tokyoreporter.com/japan-news/national/godzilla-to-receive-shinjuku-residency/ |title=Godzilla to receive Shinjuku 'residency' |date=April 5, 2015 |work=Tokyo Reporter |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Tokyu Milano-za movie theater, just west of Cinecity Square, was the largest in Japan when it opened in 1956.<ref name=K'cho-history/> Its last day of operation was December 31, 2014, closing after a screening of the film ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.alamy.com/tokyo-japan-fans-throng-the-shinjuku-milano-za-movie-theater-in-tokyos-image151340061.html |title=Fans throng the Shinjuku Milano-za movie theater in Tokyo's Shinjuku Ward on Dec. 31, 2014, the last day of its operation, to see the American film \"E.T.,\" chosen for the last screening. The movie theater, one of the largest in Japan with 1,064 seats, opened in December 1956. |author=Warnick, BJ |date=31 December 2014 |agency=Newscom |work=Alamy |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref> A {{convert|225|m|adj=on}} high skyscraper is planned to be built on the site.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://japan-forward.com/shinjuku-tokyu-milano-promises-new-ways-to-enjoy-kabuki-cho-nightlife-come-2022/ |title=Shinjuku Tokyu Milano Promises New Ways to Enjoy Kabuki-cho Nightlife Come 2022 |author=Okada, Mizuki |date=August 14, 2019 |work=Japan Forward |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Crime==\nIn 2004, according to a spokesperson of Metropolitan Tokyo, there were more than 1,000 [[yakuza]] members in Kabukich\u014d, and 120 different enterprises under their control.<ref name=\"yakuza\">2004\u5e741\u670819\u65e5\u7af9\u82b1\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u526f\u77e5\u4e8b\u767a\u8a00\u30fb\u6b4c\u821e\u4f0e\u753a\u4f4f\u6c11\u3068\u306e\u61c7\u8ac7\u4f1a</ref>{{full|date=June 2015}}\n\nEntering the new millennium, laws were more strictly enforced and patrols became more frequent. In addition, fifty [[closed-circuit camera]]s were installed in May 2002 after the [[Myojo 56 building fire]] that killed 44;<ref name=JT-2002>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2002/01/20/general/kabukicho-where-worlds-collide/ |title=Kabukicho: where worlds collide |author=Schreiber, Mark |url-access=limited |date=January 20, 2002 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=JT-2008>{{cite news |url=https://japantoday.com/category/features/lifestyle/last-call-for-kabukicho-red-light-district?comment-order=latest |title=Last call for Kabukicho red-light district |author=Bull, Brett |date=December 22, 2008 |newspaper=Japan Today |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2001/09/04/national/gas-pipes-ruled-out-as-cause-of-kabukicho-blaze/ |url-access=limited |title=Gas pipes ruled out as cause of Kabukicho blaze |date= September 4, 2001 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref> the patrols and cameras reduced criminal activities in Kabukich\u014d, amidst controversy.<ref name=TR-2008>{{cite news |url=https://www.tokyoreporter.com/japan-news/special-reports/kabukicho-comes-clean/ |title=Kabukicho comes clean |date=May 2, 2008 |work=Tokyo Reporter |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrivate citizens and government agencies launched a joint effort in July 2003, called the Shinjuku Shopping Center Committee to Expel Organized-Crime Groups, with the aim to replace unlicensed and adult-oriented businesses (which were believed to pay [[protection fees]] to organized crime groups) with legitimate businesses.<ref name=JT-2004>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2004/06/13/people/cops-and-citizens-bid-to-blitz-street-sleaze/ |url-access=limited |title=Cops and citizens bid to blitz street sleaze |author=Prideaux, Eric |date=June 13, 2004 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> In 2004, the police undertook an operation clamping down on illegal clubs and [[brothel]]s, causing many to go out of business. An amendment to the 1948 Adult Entertainment law made aggressive catching of female patrons by male hosts illegal.<ref name=TR-2008/> Also, the Kabukich\u014d Renaissance organization started in April 2008 to rid Kabukich\u014d of the yakuza; office manager Yoshihisa Shimoda stated \"[a]t the end of the day, we want Kabukicho to be clean. We want security, safety and a pleasant environment.\"<ref name=JT-2008/>\n\nIn 2011, Tokyo began to enforce the Organised Crime Exclusion Ordinance, which makes it a crime for businesses or individuals to deal with the Yakuza.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2012/08/201282115458449808.html |title=Meeting Japan's yakuza |author=Chou, Chan Tau |date=23 August 2012 |work=Al Jazeera |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> Although the punishment for violating the ordinance ranges up to one year in prison and a fine of {{JPY|50000}}, it is intended to provide an excuse for refusing to make protection payments.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/11/02/national/media-national/illegal-pay-gangs-thats-not-point/ |url-access=limited |title=It's illegal to pay gangs ... but that's not the point |author=Adelstein, Jake |date=November 2, 2019 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Host Clubs and Cabaret Club at Kabuki-ch\u014d, Shinjuku (2016-07-13 15.32.28 by Dick Thomas Johnson).jpg|thumb|right|Advertisements for host, hostess, and cabaret clubs (2016)]]\n===''Bottakuri''===\n''Bottakuri'' is a form of [[bait-and-switch]], where patrons are attracted by a low advertised price but then charged numerous hidden fees. In one instance, a group of nine was lured into a bar under the promise the all-inclusive cost was {{JPY|4000}}; the hostesses inside consumed 172 drinks and the final bill was {{JPY|2663000}}. The staff at the bar allegedly threatened the patrons to ensure payment. In 2015, there were 1,052 reported cases of ''bottakuri'' in the first four months of the year alone, particularly targeting foreign tourists from China and Korea,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/06/17/national/crime-legal/one-kabukicho-bar-allegedly-ripped-drinkers/ |url-access=limited |title=How one Kabukicho bar allegedly ripped off its drinkers |author=Kodera, Atsushi |date=June 17, 2015 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> prompting a crackdown that began in May; in July, there were only 45 reported cases of ''bottakuri'' and 28 bars had been shut down.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/08/12/national/crime-legal/police-crackdown-curbing-extortionist-kabukicho-bottakuri-bar-rip-offs/ |url-access=limited |title=Police crackdown curbing extortionist Kabukicho 'bottakuri' bar rip-offs |agency=Kyodo |date=August 12, 2015 |newspaper=Japan Times |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Aida founded the Shinjuku Kabukicho Host Club Anti-Organized Crime Gang Association to disassociate host and hostess clubs from organized crime, reduce the aggressive \"catching\" street solicitations, and eliminate the ''bottakuri'' practice.<ref name=TR-2008/>\n\n==In media==\nKabukich\u014d has been featured in:\n* [[Yakuza (video game)|''Yakuza'']] (video game), as Kamurocho<ref>{{cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/how-yakuzas-city-changes-from-game-to-game-1821884988 |title=How ''Yakuza''{{'}}s City Changes From Game To Game |author=Alexandra, Heather |date=8 January 2018 |work=Kotaku |accessdate=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n* ''[[Gin Tama]]'' (manga)\n* ''[[City Hunter]]'' (manga)\n* ''[[Tokyo Vice]]'' (2009 memoir by [[Jake Adelstein]])\n* ''[[Shin Petshop of Horrors]]'' (manga) <ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pet_Shop_of_Horrors</ref>\n* ''[[Weathering with You]]'' (film)<ref>{{cite web|last=Salupen|first=Mark|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2019/10/01/films/the-real-tokyo-locations-from-makoto-shinkais-anime-movies/|title=The real Tokyo locations from Makoto Shinkai's anime movies|newspaper=[[The Japan Times]]|date=1 October 2019|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Case File n\u00ba221: Kabukicho]] (anime television series)\n{{clear}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Shinjuku Theatre+Shinjuku Koma Feb1960.jpg|Shinjuku Koma, looking north from the east end of Cinecity Square (Feb 1960)\nFile:Tokyo Shinjuku Milano za.jpg|Tokyu Milano-za (2012), looking west from Cinecity Square\nFile:Central Road Kabukicho-Sinjyuku-Tokyo.jpg|Kabukich\u014d, view north along Central toward Toho Building\nFile:Shinjuku Toho1.jpg|Shinjuku Toho Building\nFile:Tokyo Route 302 -06.jpg|View east along Yasukuni-Dori, the southern border of Kabukich\u014d.\nFile:Kabukicho-Shinjuku-Tokyo 20120204.jpg|View east along Yasukuni-Dori at night.\nFile:I love Kabukicho (29262192243).jpg|I \u2665 Kabuki-ch\u014d sign.\nFile:Sakura Dori street Kabukicho-Sinjyuku-Tokyo.jpg|Gate at Sakura-Dori, looking north from Yasukuni-Dori\nFile:Shinjuku 06.JPG|Prominent signs along Sakura-Dori (\u3055\u304f\u